As for your second question: As far as I can tell, the table you show does not appear to provide odds ratios, but the results from linear regression models (leaving aside that the table appears to be messed up, at least with respect to the last three columns). The values shown are beta coefficients (since outcome and predictors were z-scored -- which makes the B and beta columns redundant). If you want a partial correlation coefficient here, you can just compute B/SE to get the test statistic. Together with the number of predictors and the total sample size, one can then compute the partial correlation coefficient from this information. But I cannot tell you which of the models you should use for this (this is a substantive question).

Best,
Wolfgang

